Trinidadian Canadian ballerina Tina Pereira (@ballerinacouture) joined the National Ballet of Canada (@nationalballet) in 2001, steadily climbing the ranks before reaching principal dancer in 2021. Here, she talks about how she manages fast tempos, why she started her own leotard line and her secret to success. 

Read it on Pointe+ at the link in our bio! 💕

The last 10 days as Cinderella have been some of the most fulfilling moments on stage! Not only do I love Cindy, but this ballet also features so many of my amazing colleagues and we celebrated the careers of two of our National Ballet icons who I was thrilled to share the last show with 😍. A very special moment in time I will cherish forever! ✨

location.city_name: Sony Center for the Performing Arts

social_posts.post_text:
Reflecting on the power of collaboration and resilience with ‘Smoke V’ – a choreographic gem I created on the remarkable @ballerinacouture in 2019 for @unitedway Greater Toronto. What an honour. Witness part the historic journey of Tina, now the first Colored Female principal in Canadian dance history with the @nationalballet of Canada. Tina is a proud ballerina of Caribbean descent. And me being from the Bahamas felt like a spiritual and historical match made in heaven. 
Bahamas and Trinidad represent!!
🇧🇸🇹🇹

Amidst challenges, let’s not forget our major accomplishments. Proud  for this work to have premiered at the iconic Sony Center, the former home of the National Ballet. 🇨🇦🩰✨ 

#DanceHistory #EquityInArt #SmokeV #TinaPereira #nicholasrosechoreography #nationalballetofcanada
